@dawnranger: I can reproduce the crash if the model is given an input of [batch_size][seq_length=0]. Is that possible in your case? I'll fix MlasGemm to bail out early if M/N/K is zero. 

After running with that fix though, I hit a problem in the Reshape kernel where it fails to compute that the -1 dimension can be 256 because the shape size is zero. That would be a different problem to resolve. The ONNX shape inferencing code might have better logic to compute the unknown dimension.

While these issues are being worked out, can you avoid calling into the runtime when seq_length=0?

issue.title: MLAS: handle MlasGemm(M/N/K==0) cases

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Update the floating point GEMM routines to handle the case where any of M/N/K are zero.

**Motivation and Context**
This fixes the crash from #6232 where one of the GEMM parameters was zero inside the LSTM op. Many ops were already bailing out early if the output tensor size was zero, but this should be handled more robustly inside MLAS.

The DGEMM code has been resynchronized with the SGEMM code (this code still needs to be templated to avoid some of the code duplication).

The unit test has been updated to exercise the M/N/K is zero path.

The document means: if your system is 32bits x86, then you should add the "--x86" flag. Otherwise, you don't. By default it is x86_64.
